I wanted to share with the group an app that a friend recommended. I’ve been using it now for a couple of weeks and have been completely mind-blown! The free version allows you to scan a food or cosmetic product and see a detailed description of all harmful substances it contains in a very user-friendly rating format. If you pay the subscription (which is whatever you decide) you can search products. I have to say that I will be rethinking a lot of products that we currently use- from cosmetics that I put on my skin daily to sunscreen brands, breakfast foods that my kids eat all the time… yikes! https://apps.apple.com/us/app/yuka-food-cosmetic-scanner/id1092799236
I have been using for a while now! Loving it!!
https://www.ewg.org/skindeep/ This is also a really great resource. Very eye opening😬 for better or for worse😂
I was drinking an oat milk with dangerous ingredients! Thanks to the app I’ve found a safe one
Just an example out of 1000

The whole day is different! I’m so sorry. Mine calmed down with twenty minutes. I didn’t do daycare, but maybe sometime who did can chime in with ideas?

I’m really sorry you’re going through this, Laisa.  I don’t have the exact experience, but I would recommend talking to the Director at your daycare to see how they can help support you both in this transition.

With my youngest, we started in one daycare and only lasted 4 days because it was clear that the Director and assistant director (who I interfaced with) were not supportive during the transition period.

We are at Sunrise now and it has been a totally different experience.  The director and teachers are so helpful — especially when we’ve been away and it’s hard for my son to transition back into the classroom.

Oh no that’s really hard. How old is the baby and which daycare? Honestly when I see new babies at daycare I see some do cry on and off for the whole day and then by 2 weeks later they are smiling and they are bonded with the teachers. I agree with Val to have a conversation with the director. You can try doing shorter days in the beginning if you could.

Mine was super sensitive during the first two months when he started daycare at 1yo. For the first two weeks or so, he would cry almost all day unless this one teacher came into his class that we spent some time together when we toured the center. My theory is that spending time together when we were around might have given my son a sense of security towards that teacher. So I went pickup earlier and spent some time playing there before going home (not drop off so they don’t get even more sad when you leave). After building some trust with one of his infant teachers, he would no longer cry when that teacher is present and then he slowly warmed up to other teachers.

My toddler is going to need some vaccines soon and I have no idea how to go about this! Do I need a Paediatrician? In Canada, everything was done by family doctors
For flu/covid, if they are over 3, you can often get them at a pharmacy. For all other vaccines or for toddlers younger than 3, we go to the pediatrician.
Yes! Pediatricians here will keep your child up to date on all vaccines and flu shots
She’s 18 months so a pediatrician! How do I go about getting one? Do I just call around and see who’s taking patients?

You could try that. But you could also leverage your health insurance to find a pediatrician. Typically they will list which doctors near you accept your insurance and that’s a good way to find a doctor. There should be a number on your insurance card for help like that, or normally you can log into their website if you made the account etc. But if you call them they can advise you. You could also call doctors directly and ask if they accept your insurance. A lot of people in the north end go to north end waterfront health on Hanover (doctors lopreste, turnock, mcloughlin are all highly regarded) and other places nearby. Lot of options for healthcare which is good.

I personally like using the main hospitals, so either tufts or MGH - that way, when your pediatrician is not in the office, you are still able to see somebody within the group without having to establish care all over again and all your brisk history ends up being in the same computer system that they all have access to
Which is so helpful for late night er or urgent care visits or some day sick appointments
Pediatricians or family physicians.

My only other tip would be to try to get in somewhere that is closest to you… We were using Tufts in the beginning because we couldn’t get into MGH. The waitlist was too long at the time and just going to Tufts and going through their parking and getting inside and doing the check-in and all of that… Took so much longer than it does now at the MGH branch and Charlestown, it’s such a timesaver! A lot of people in the North end are very happy with the North end waterfront clinic for example

We go to Atrius Health and love it. There’s a location on milk st so it’s very walkable. My baby sees the same family doctor I see and the office is available 24/7 for any emergencies. I’d definitely recommend and it’s a large network of locations so there may be availability somewhere for an initial visit/vaccinations. I use them for all my care - pcp, ob gyn, dermatology and have had really great experiences.
I second Atrius health/harvard vanguard. They are amazing and we see all of our doctors there.
We also go to this office and see a few doctors there.  Always have had a positive experience with them.

Anyone have advice on how to get rid of cradle cap without their hair falling out with it?! 

I have the Frida comb set, and baby shampoo, and tubby Todd AOO… I’ve heard they all work great but haven’t heard about how it works on a baby with hair!! Since my understanding is the cradle cap is just cosmetic, and not harmful, I def don’t want to treat it if it means his cute hair will come out!

Cleansing oil (or even baby oil will do) on dry hair/scalp. Massage it in, it will loosen the cradle cap and lift it off the scalp. Then you just gently comb it out with very fine-toothed comb and shampoo after. Never lost any hair with that method but got rid of the cap easily.
I’m

Era Organics Healing Ointment for... https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0194EGJRK?ref=ppx_pop_mob_ap_share

I used this on my daughter who had lots of hair, I would massage it in and leave it in for a day or so and then use a fine tooth comb to brush it out, never had any hair loss

I used olive oil, a small amount and rub gently into babies (dry) scalp. I used a soft toothbrush. I put a little cap on him for like 10 minutes and let it soak in. The flakes soak the oil and lift off. Then I used the very fine tooth comb from the hospital and gently ran across the scalp to lift the flakes. Then I gave a bath and washed his hair using those little silicon pads (like from Frieda baby) to wash the scalp and the oil. You could even not do a bath and just wash the hair on the swaddled baby in the sink like at the salon. I did it daily or every other day until it was resolved. Worked very quickly tho, like 2 or 3 sessions only.

To get rid of cradle cap, I applied olive oil to my son’s head, placed a plastic bag on top, and put a hat over it. I waited for about an hour. Then, I gave him a bath and used a baby shampoo while combing his hair. Everything came off without any sores or hair loss, and it never came back.
Vaseline/aquaphor worked best for us… but the hair sure looked greasy after 😂

Hi, I just found 1 head lice (louse?) in my 1 year old 's hair! 😭😭 she has baby hair, so it was easy to spot. I thought it was a gnat, but when I took it out and took a photo... it's a lice. 
Are we screwed? Any recommendations for what to do? 
She goes to daycare......

I've heard very good things about this product (from my SIL who is a hairdresser and her kid had lice) ... https://fairytaleshaircare.com/collections/rosemary-repel?gad_source=1&gclid=CjwKCAjw6c63BhAiEiwAF0EH1GqRZuu3t9pNW5QcV-3PmccCYTt7iykQGtWuNo3LqJXVAA3EH3GDRBoCHg0QAvD_BwE
They sell it at Philip's Salon on Hanover Street. I bought the conditioning spray just as a preventative.

Wear your hair in a ponytail daily if it’s long. Wash and dry on HOT all of her bedding, stuffies, blankets, coats and recent clothes she has worn. If it can’t be dried on hot then bag it up for 2 weeks. Those things are done to kill any eggs. 

I would also bag up any soft toys and unused blankets for now until it’s gone so you have less items to worry about washing/drying. If you are worried about your own hair, blow dry it on high heat at the scalp tonight as long as you can tolerate it. The fairy tales shampoo mentioned is great as well. I also always used a tea tree oil shampoo on myself for prevention. Please tell her daycare teachers so they can let the other parents know (and so they can take preventative measures themselves).

Good morning. I have a good friend , she’s at the end of first trimester (1st baby) super sick, throwing up every morning , asking for advice what she should take/eat/drink . I was never sick with my both pregnancies so I have no idea what to tell her

There’s medication if it’s really bad. I found eating to stay ahead of it really helped me. Like bland foods, like rice crackers. once you’re hungry it’s a lot worse. Also for me it did wrap up around 14 weeks, so maybe it would start to wind down for her as well.
Same same. I would usually start my morning off with a bowl of plain pasta or toast. Helped a lot. Good luck!

I ended up only eating brown rice with yeast flakes,that was pretty much my food for months 2 and 3. Electrolytes and coconut water are really important too. Some people swear by ginger although it didn’t help me much
I kept ritz crackers everywhere in the house and would eat one or two and it would help so much.
Also, my doctor SIL sent me these and they helped, too! There’s different flavors online as well
https://a.co/d/9SXY1Q9
I second everything that’s been said! Also ginger ale with ice cubes and vitamin B6 helped me
For some weird reason applesauce always helped me 🤷🏽‍♀️😂

To my knowledge, it’s offered at some daycares and other small educational institutions and is another free alternative if you don’t get into the Elliott, Warren Prescott or Harvard Kent in our areas

UPK is program where the city of Boston will pay for a seat at a private school or childcare center for a child of a Boston resident regardless of income level. Applications will open in the spring, BPS will post the exact date some time during the winter, check their page every so often. Starting from the most recent cycle (this past spring) they took away schools’ ability to assign those seats based on the school’s decision (whatever number of seats the UPK program commits to fund for each school), for example before schools were able to give those seats to siblings of current students. Now it’s on first-come-first serve basis. So it’s basically means you get all your required document ready to go on your computer (like birth certificate, residency proof etc.), create your account in the system well in advance, set the alarm and the moment the registration opens you fill it out *as quick as possible* and hit submit button. Do not go back in and edit your form because it will move your spot in line to the later submission time.

It’s acetic acid bacteria and lacto bacillus plus some yeast. Essentially probiotics. 
The problem with any home made brew (yogurt, or any boozy /sugary thing) is that it can also contain salmonella and listeria. That’s the concern.

Hi all, two travel related questions I’m hoping someone has experience with! Does anyone know if you can bring food through security at the airport (not packaged snacks but like a sandwich or salad or cooked food in a take out container?). I’m reading about this online but it’s not entirely clear and wondering if anyone has personal experience? 

Also, is there a way to download content onto an iPad so you can watch it without any internet at all? Last time we flew with my daughter I downloaded a bunch of shows in the PBS Kids App but they were still inside the app, meaning you needed some internet to open the app and access them, even if you didn’t need internet to stream them. The WiFi was broken the plane, so we were out of luck 🙄 Hoping to avoid this next time!

You can bring food! Food is subject to the rule about liquids which TSA defines as anything that will form to the container it’s in (e.g. peanut butter, pudding, etc.). If you explain to TSA that the food is for kids, they will usually just test it and let you through. 

Netflix, Prime, Disney+, and Hulu all have content you can download as part of your monthly subscription. It’s housed in the app, but it doesn’t need any internet connection once downloaded.

Can anyone recommend a New England ski resort for a family of 5?

4 & 5 year old have never skied hoping to get them in a lesson. Hubby has also rarely skied and will do an adult lesson. lol

We grew up going to Butternut Mountain in Great Barrington. It’s a great mountain for kids and has tubing! 

The only bummer is that it’s not a true resort, there’s a lot of nearby hotels, airbnbs and other rentals. 

The mountain itself I can’t recommend enough. They’ve got a GREAT kid section for new skiers/snowboarders.

Okemo Mountain in Ludlow, VT! Great family mountain with great instructors. Their resort (Jackson Gore) has an indoor/outdoor pool and some of the condo rentals have pools as well. They also have tubing and a mountain coaster and I think some other fun things like that. There is a restaurant there but also more restaurants downtown. Feel free to PM me if you want more info! We’ve been going there since I was a kid.

Those parenting classes can be great and helpful and sometimes for some kids and families they don’t work. She is absolutely amazing!

Here is a little about her experience:

	•	Experienced with the TakingCaraBabies method. She always kept our baby on schedule with his naps and understood the importance of wake windows for his bedtime.
	•	Six years of experience as a nanny, beginning as an Au Pair. She started caring for our baby when he was 6 months old, but she has experience with babies as young as 1 month up to children 8 years old.

SHARING

What do you mean by “additional”? You mean more frequent mammograms or some other imaging/diagnostic methods (ultrasound etc)?

I had that once and it turned out ok, it's quite common
Yes I yea quite common it’s just the nature of the tissue  I’m just curious if I should push for extra regular screening of some type

I’ve been reading a lot about this. It feels like practitioners recommend MRI’s and/or ultrasounds for dense tissue to complement the Mammo (since it’s not as good as detecting cancer in dense breasts). I think you have to ask for it. I was called back after my regular screening to do an ultra sound because of this. I go to Harvard Vanguard in Kenmore Square and they got me right in. I’m thinking about asking my PCP if we can do an ultrasound every time

Thanks this is so helpful this is what I was wondering. Seems like nowadays you kind of have to be your own doctor in some cases, and I was thinking this might be that case. OK, I think I’m gonna really inquire and ask for additional screening. Thanks for sharing!!!

I have dense tissue as well and I see someone at Brigham's Breast Center for a manual checkup every year. The doctor told me that they don't straight out recommend MRIs because they have a high rate of false positives (something shocking like 20%, don't quote me on this). And so if you get a positive that leads to painful biopsies and lots of anxiety. I also inquired about ultrasounds but she told me they don't really do them anymore. Thanks this is helpful!! Yeah I remember reading research about increased screening in Japan. Causes a lot more detection, but like you said more false positives. It’s an interesting balance.
I have dense breast tissue and asked my PCP if I should get more frequent exams and they said no, yearly is  fine for me. But to make sure I perform my at home exams.

Just chiming in! Totally normal to develop fears and how we respond can make all the difference. I like to think about teaching kids why we have fears. Anxiety is normal and natural and can be really helpful because it can help us keep our senses safe. For instance, if we are out hiking and see a bear, feeling anxious helps us figure out if we need to freeze, fight, or run. But sometimes our anxiety fires when there is no real threat (nighttime, being away from a caregiver, etc). Our tendency as parents is to say you’re safe! Nothing bad will happen! While that reassurance will help reduce anxiety short term, it makes anxiety have more control over us long term. Instead we want to think about being anxiety or bravery detectives, so saying ok, your feel anxious or fearful, let’s look for clues to see if you’re really unsafe. Then you can help your child reappraise the fear and realize nothing bad will happen and then you can really help boost them up and praise them for being brave! For instance, ok, you’re looking under your bed, you don’t see any monsters. We’ll have to have you go to bed and see if anything bad happens. Wow you woke up and were totally safe! Good job being brave and figuring out there are no monsters under the bed! Believe it or not, even kids at this young age can have impairing levels of anxiety, so if anyone needs more individualized support, happy to help connect you to more resources. Also highly recommend this book written by a wonderful and expert anxiety clinician:https://www.amazon.com/You-Your-Anxious-Child-Worries/dp/1583334955?dplnkId=cb545c73-138c-4783-b262-e088db53bea8&nodl=1

Just chiming in to say that we complete the thinking when my kids are afraid, and it works about 50% of the time. So with the robots throwing you in the trash example, we would say, wow, that does sound super scary. But if someone put you in the trash, what would you do? You’d probably crawl out again, right? And yell “hey, don’t throw me in the trash robot!”And then probably take a bath because you’d be stinky. I find that completing the loop of the story to get to something positive that gives them agency makes them a little less freaked out. But it doesn’t always work! Sometimes their brains come up with really creepy stuff. Good luck!
Creepy stuff, exactly! Even I get scared 😅

How do you moms manage travelling with infants between 6mo -1 year old, in terms of food? We are planning a 2-3 days trip outside boston. Not sure how can I prepare and feed my baby all her solids?

When my son was that age, I chose restaurants where I could order dishes suitable for him, like fish with no seasoning, vegetables that I could mash with a fork, mashed potatoes, rice, etc. I also bought fruits/berries from stores to have as snacks on the go. I bought in advance veggie-broth-based purees and other healthy snacks with me. I made sure to pack everything we might need so I wouldn’t have to search for it in stores during the trip.

I remember bringing store bought baby food with me. Didn’t do much ( if anything) in terms of cooking/preparing. If we were eating out and there was something we could order for ourselves that would also be okay to mash a little on the side for our son, we would try to do that.

I will also say I remember stressing out so much about my first trip away with my child that my husband and I almost canceled lol we decided to go and all turned out fine. We just figured out the food stuff like others said. If they are not eating the exact same stuff they eat at home they’ll be fine and you can get what you need food wise almost anywhere! Good luck and enjoy your trip! ❤️

Hi moms, any effective cough remedy for 3 year olds? I know if I call my pede they’ll tell me to wait the full two weeks, and I’m not sure I can do another week of no sleep. Thanks

A few of our favorites (my 6 month old just fought off RSV over Christmas): 

-Zarbees chest rub
-Boogie wipes
-Saline spray
-A bulb or snot sucker
-Humidifier

I’ve also heard good things about the mommy’s bliss brand cough syrup! We didn’t try because it contains honey but should be safe for your 3 yo (just be sure to read the specifications on the bottle)! 

Also lots of steam showers! We just passed my little one into the shower anytime me or my husband took one and that seemed to help.

Good luck ❤️

Idk how effective anything is as we throw everything at the wall and hope something works but we've done... Chamomile tea with manuka honey, hylands cough meds, Vicks vapor rub at night all over his chest and back, crank humidifier.

Hi moms, not sure this is solvable but throwing it out there anyway incase anyone has any advice. It’s a sleep question. My 4yo wants to stay up until 8:30/9pm every night. He sleeps through the night in his own bed- great. But it doesn’t really work for me because then he sleeps past 6:30/7am which is when I need him up so we can leave for work. I really hate to have to wake him up if he needs the sleep. But If I put him to bed early (like 7:30/8pm) he wakes up in the middle of the night (1am), comes to my bed (fine) and then basically has a split night and is up for an hour asking me questions. and then he ends up sleeping in even later in the morning!!!! Disaster. Any tips? Normally it’s not a big deal but my 15mo old has me up all night anyway demanding milk so I’m just really needing something to improve. Thanks for any advice!!!

Is there anyway you can stop pulling him into your bed if you do the earlier bed time? YMMV, but at four, I explained to my son that I needed my own sleep to be a nice mommy who plays games, and that waking me up in the middle of the night made it hard to have fun later that day. He kind of got it. It at least helped me feel less guilty to explain that there was a good reason for me to get sleep – not that anyone needs a reason to get a basic human need!  We also made a separate bed in our room (on a couch we had there but a blow up would work) and said he could sleep in it at any time if he didn’t wake us up. If he woke us I matched him back to bed (and pretended not to notice when he tiptoed back into the bed in my room without waking me.) After his brother arrived, I think he just really wanted to be close to us in the middle of the night and that was fine so long as he didn’t wake anybody! Then we had extra snuggles for the 10 minutes before we got out of bed. I think this pretty complicated pattern lasted about four months. Just a thought in case it could help!

Sorry in advance for long text, but passing along a LAX opportunity for girls (and boys) in No End. Our 1st grade girl will be doing the travel team, think she’s most excited for the friends, goggles and uniform, but none the less should be great fun with great coaches.  If interested in No. End LAX:

The NEAA will be kicking off its third season of lacrosse in March!  The program, under the team name Midnight Riders, will compete in the Mass Youth Lacrosse (MYL) league again this spring.  Both boys and girls teams will be registered with MYL at the 1st/2nd grade level and the 3rd/4th grade level, playing 8 total games on Sunday mornings starting March 30th and running through June 1st.  Home games will be played here in the North End on the Puopolo Park fields while away games will be played in the greater Boston metro area against local opponents.  

The NEAA will also be running its traditional Fundamentals Clinic on Sunday afternoons, which has been a hit amongst kids in the North End the last few years.  Boys and girls ages 4-11 years old are invited to participate in a weekly clinic introducing the fundamentals of lacrosse.  For 6 sessions on Sundays from 3:30-4:45pm, they'll be on the North End fields working through the basics of throwing, catching and scooping a lacrosse ball while blasting music and playing fun kids games.  

To register or ask any questions, you can reach out to the Director of NEAA Lacrosse, David Paolisso @ dpaolisso@gmail.com.  Registration link is: https://www.neaasports.org/register/form/221093232.

The new URL for the N.E.A.A. website is : https://www.neaasports.org

Hi everyone, I wanted to put in a little plug for the Boston Children’s School (BCS), if anyone is in the process of exploring preschools. It is an incredibly special place, thanks to the dedication of the wonderful teachers and the Director, Judy Langer, who has been guiding the school for decades. The environment at BCS is so warm and welcoming, and the small class sizes allow the teachers to give each child plenty of thoughtful attention and support. 

Enrollment is open for Fall 2025, and they have a very fun a summer program as well. Feel free to call Judy with questions or for help with registration: 617-367-6239 or 617-BCS-KIDS.

I agree with the other moms, but wanted to make an additional recommendation about the burp cloths. I especially loved using muslin cloths - they are light, dry super fast and you can tie them around their neck later on when they start teething/ drooling or as a non-itching scarf. I still have some from 10 years ago- now using them as kitchen towels. 10-15 squares 
 should be enough.

Adding to all the great advice above: the hospital will usually give you the Philips newborn pacifiers so no need to buy those particular ones. For burp cloths, a friend recommending buying a cheap pack of washcloths at Target, and that came in super handy for my girls because they were light weight and super easy to throw in the wash. I forget if it was the birthing class or lactation consultant, but I was told not to cover the hands because they use them to signal when they are hungry (putting them in their mouth) and the scratches aren’t a big deal (I remember she noted none of us are walking around with scars from scratching ourselves as newborns). But as another mom already noted, keeping up with trimming the nails also works to prevent scratches.
We still have our 30 amazon washcloths from 6 years ago when they were born and we use the for all sorts of things!

For pacifiers, the only thing I'd mention is that we decided to remove them early (~7 months) because one of my girls was becoming so reliant on them and I was worried they would continue needing them into toddlerhood (and there are some dental concerns with pacifiers being used when they're older). That was a TOUGH phase. Long story short: pacifiers are great in the short term but can be difficult to remove later on!

I really liked the wubanub pacifier with the giraffe and lobster, it had enough weight in that little stuffy to help keep the pacifier from slipping out of their mouth since they can't really keep it in as new borns.
Also, footies and mitten cuffs were great because it kept their hands and feet covered while sleeping.

To make brushing teeth more interesting for our son, we usually suggest brushing the teeth of his toys, cars, etc. We’ve been brushing his teeth since he was 6 months old. Now he’s almost 3, but he still sometimes refuses. Recently, I got so tired of trying to convince him in a positive way that I showed him pictures of toothless people saying that this will happen if you don’t brush your teeth. Now, I sometimes use that as an argument: “Remember the toothless people you saw?” 11-month-old probably wouldn’t be interested in that. However, brushing the teeth of toys would likely catch his attention and then he might be more willing to brush his own teeth.

The advice I got when my youngest did this was to try not to have a big reaction when she hurts you (as hard as that is to do!). If you do, she’ll think it’s a game and keep doing it. Then take her off the breast. She’ll learn quickly that if she wants to eat she can’t bite down/twist/etc. This helped a lot for me when I went through the same situation with my girls.

The other thing to consider - have you had any changes in your milk supply? I had a really fast let down on one side, and one of my girls used to pull her head back while still attached as a way to deal with the flow. I’ve known other moms who experienced something similar when their supplies dropped after returning to work.
My let down has always been pretty moderate. I don't think anything has changed there. I appreciate the advice! Thank you! ❤️

Part of the commando thing (as opposed to naked from the waist down) is about the fact that some kids have trouble pushing down two layers of clothes (rather than one) on their own. Or that two layers can feel thicker/more like a diaper (esp in winter). So if daycare insists on both underwear and pants, I would just go for looser/lighter weight underwear and pants for the first few days. We did a three day method and sent my daughter back to school on day 4 with like loose, boy short style underwear that wasn’t too snug and some sort of loose pants that she had practiced with at home, and that worked fine.

K0 - adding 1 (2 total)
K1 - adding 1 (4 total)
K2 - same (4 total)

which means that if you are applying for K0 and K1, you have a better chance than usual. If you are applying to K1 and you don’t get in, you have close to zero chance to get in the following year in K2, as the 4x K1 classes will take all the spots in the existing 4x K2 classes.

Hi all! Do you have any suggestions on how to convince my daughter to blow her nose? She refuses to do it saying she doesn’t know how to do it… how did you do with your kids?

I think I held up the Frida snot sucker and said ‘do you want mama to use this or do you want to blow your own nose?’
 He did not want the snot sucker and blew his own nose. He didn’t start blowing his own nose consistently until 3.5 though.
Yes I tried that too!! But her answer is I don’t know how to blow my nose 😅

I learned a trick from a woman on Instagram a little while ago. I’ll try to find the video.
But instead of asking strong willed children to do something, you ask them if they are big enough, brave enough or strong enough to do it instead. And they’re usually willing to prove that they are any one of those things. I’ve used this trick a handful of times on my son and typically works like a charm, as long as he’s not already worked up.
There’s also a little thing you could try by putting a cotton ball inside of an empty toilet paper roll and making game out of them trying to blow it through the other side with their nose.
I told my son to  pretend like he blows a balloon with his nose. Worked very well ))

To the extent it’s about not knowing how to blow her nose, I love this book for helping build breath awareness in kids: 
https://bookshop.org/p/books/alphabreaths-the-abcs-of-mindful-breathing-christopher-willard/9832472

I can’t take credit for this (as my Mom taught my daughter this without me knowing, ha)…she taught her to take a deep breath in, and then blow the air out of your nose to make the tissue dance./boogie (pun intended).  She loved trying to make the tissue move, but I also would say it’s either make the tissue dance or I would hold up the Frida (which was a life saver was she was pre being able to grasp the boogie dance).  We still use the take a deep breath and blow trick today (she’s nearly 7)
